jus algoritmi: The new digital Homo Sacer and democracy’s devastating “Policy Debt”

Author’s Note:

These essays are summaries of chapters in a larger book, a work in progress. The book covers the history of AI to present and its impact beyond AGI, consciousness, and jobs — into the nature of the citizen, our rights, ethics, and morality. It examines how AI is shaping who we are becoming, not from a technical, economic, or philosophical standpoint alone, but within the pragmatic scope of an individual's agency. It asks the question what is the right to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness in the Age of AI? Below is a summary of research and ideas for a chapter on the collapse of the public and private sphere and how AI is changing that — and democracy — for all of us. It is, at best, a preview.

The Room of One’s Own
In 1958, Hannah Arendt made an observation so quiet it almost vanished beneath the weight of its own implications. In The Human Condition, she described the ancient Greek distinction between the public and private realms not as a matter of preference or convenience but as the very architecture of what it meant to be human. The public realm — the polis — was the space of action, of speech, of appearing before others as a distinct and unrepeatable self. The private realm — the household, the body, the interior — was the space of necessity, of sustenance, of everything required to keep a person alive so that they might become someone in public.

Neither realm made sense without the other. The private gave you a self. The public gave that self somewhere to go.

What Arendt understood, and what philosopher Jürgen Habermas would later trace with the precision of an intellectual cartographer in The Structural Transformation of the Public Sphere, was that the boundary between these two realms was not incidental to democratic life. It was democratic life. The public sphere — that space where private individuals came together as a public to deliberate, to argue, to hold power accountable — depended entirely on the existence of a private domain from which those individuals could emerge. You had to have an interior life in order to bring something to the public conversation. You had to have a room you could close the door on.

Richard Sennett, writing in The Fall of Public Man, saw the erosion beginning as early as the nineteenth century — the slow bleed of private sentiment into public life, the creeping expectation that public figures reveal their inner selves, that authenticity replace rhetoric, that feeling replace argument. What Sennett diagnosed was not simply a cultural shift but a structural weakening: when the private begins to colonize the public, the public loses its capacity to function as a space of collective deliberation. It becomes instead a theater of confession.

But none of them — not Arendt, nor Habermas, nor Sennett — could have anticipated the inversion that was coming. They worried about the private leaking into the public. They did not foresee the public devouring the private whole.

This collapsing of the private and public sphere can be illustrated through several stages. Each stage collapses more of the boundary that democratic life depends on, and together they have produced a crisis that reaches far beyond privacy into the foundations of citizenship, political agency, and the capacity of democratic institutions to govern at all.

The Cubicle and the Gaze
The first collapse came not through technology but through architecture.
There is a detail in the history of surveillance that most people encounter backwards. The panopticon — Jeremy Bentham's circular prison design that Michel Foucault made the centerpiece of Discipline and Punish — was not originally designed for prisoners. It was designed for workers. Bentham's brother Samuel built the first version in Russia in the late eighteenth century: a circular factory floor where inexperienced laborers could be observed from a single central point. Jeremy Bentham generalized the concept, saw its potential for prisons, schools, hospitals — any institution that needed to produce docile, productive bodies. But the origin was the workplace. Surveillance began not as punishment but as management.
Foucault understood what this meant. The genius of the panopticon was not that it watched everyone all the time — that would be expensive and impractical. The genius was that it could be watching at any moment, and the observed could never be certain whether they were being seen. The effect was internalization. You began to watch yourself. You disciplined your own behavior because the architecture made it impossible to know when you were free from the gaze.
The modern office reproduced this structure with eerie fidelity. The cubicle — open from above, visible to passing managers, your screen angled outward — was a panopticon flattened into carpeted rectangles. The open-plan office that replaced it was worse: now there were no walls at all. You were perpetually visible, perpetually performing the appearance of productivity, perpetually aware that someone might be looking.
What the workplace did to the public/private boundary was subtle and total. Before the modern office, work was a place you went. You left your home — your private realm — and entered a public or semi-public space where you performed a role. The boundary was physical, temporal, clear. You crossed a threshold. You came home.
The cubicle began to dissolve that threshold. Not because the work followed you home — that would come later — but because the gaze followed you everywhere within the workplace. There was no private moment in the office. No space where you were simply yourself, unobserved, free to think or feel or exist without performing. The workplace became a space where the private self had no permission to exist.
Mike Judge understood this with the clarity of satire. In Office Space — released in 1999, at the precise hinge point between the old surveillance and the new — Peter Gibbons' liberation is not a change of circumstance but a change of orientation toward the gaze. He stops caring whether he is being watched. He stops performing. And the system, which depends entirely on internalized self-surveillance, has no mechanism to process a person who simply opts out of being seen.
The dream sequence where his boss Lumbergh appears in his bedroom is not a throwaway joke. It is the film's thesis: the workplace gaze has penetrated the last private space. The office is in the bedroom now. There is no threshold left to cross.
If Office Space is the moment pop culture recognized the collapse, the Apple TV series Severance is the moment it recognized there was no way back. Created by Dan Erickson and released in 2022, the show takes the problem this essay is tracing and makes it surgical: what if the only way to restore the boundary between work and private life is to split the self in two? Lumon Industries offers its employees a procedure — a chip implanted in the brain that creates two completely separate consciousnesses. The "innie" exists only at work, with no memory of the outside world. The "outie" goes home each night with no knowledge of what happened during the workday. The boundary is restored. The cost is that neither half is a person.
This is not workplace surveillance anymore. This is AI dissolving the self and rebuilding it according to corporate specifications. The innie has no private life — no family, no memory, no interiority beyond the walls of Lumon's fluorescent corridors. The outie has privacy but has surrendered agency over half of their waking existence to a consciousness they will never meet. And Lumon — the corporation, the oligarchy in miniature — controls the technology, defines what each half is permitted to know and feel, and makes the sovereign decision about where the line falls. The algorithm is no longer watching. It is partitioning the self. What Han describes as the shift from subject to project, Severance dramatizes as the shift from person to product — two incomplete products, manufactured by the same machine, neither of which possesses the wholeness that political agency requires.
Where Office Space showed us a man trying to escape the gaze, Severance shows us a world where the gaze has been so thoroughly internalized that escape requires becoming two people, neither of whom is free.
And between them — between 1999 and 2022 — something happened that made Severance legible in a way it never could have been when Office Space was released. Remote work, accelerated by the pandemic but building for years before it, completed what the cubicle started. The office didn't just follow you home in a dream sequence anymore. It moved in. The laptop open on the kitchen table, the Zoom camera framing your living room, the Slack notification pinging at 10 p.m. from the same device your child uses to watch cartoons — remote work didn't free people from the workplace panopticon. It dissolved the last physical boundary between the workspace and the private realm entirely. Your home became the office. Your bedroom became the cubicle. The threshold that Peter Gibbons' dream sequence warned was dissolving simply ceased to exist. Office Space imagined the boss in your bedroom as a nightmare. Remote work made it a calendar invite. Severance arrived in a culture that already understood, viscerally, that the boundary was gone — and its premise resonated precisely because millions of people had spent two years discovering that there was no room left to close the door on.
The Profile and the Performance
If the cubicle was the first collapse — the workspace consuming the private self within its walls — the second collapse was the voluntary one. And it arrived with the seductive promise of connection.

José Van Dijck, in The Culture of Connectivity, traced how social media platforms did not simply provide a new public square but fundamentally restructured the relationship between the self that exists and the self that is presented. The profile is not a person. It is a performance of a person — curated, edited, optimized for an audience that is always watching. Where the cubicle made you visible against your will, the profile made you visible by design. You built your own panopticon and called it self-expression.

Mark Zuckerberg said it plainly in 2010, with the unnerving confidence of someone who does not understand what he is describing: “Having two identities for yourself is an example of a lack of integrity.” As Michael Zimmer documented, this was not a casual remark. It was a design philosophy. Facebook was built on the premise that the private self and the public self should be the same self — that the boundary between them was not a feature of human complexity but a bug to be eliminated.

What Zuckerberg called integrity, Sennett would have recognized as the final stage of the collapse he had diagnosed decades earlier. The expectation of a single, consistent, transparent self — visible to employers, friends, family, strangers, algorithms — is not authenticity. It is the abolition of the interior. It is the demand that you have no room you can close the door on.

Fred Turner, in From Counterculture to Cyberculture, traced the ideological roots of this demand back to the communal experiments of the 1960s — the belief that transparency and openness would produce liberation, that walls were oppressive, that the free flow of information would set everyone free. What the communes discovered, and what Silicon Valley inherited without learning the lesson, was that the abolition of privacy does not produce freedom. It produces conformity. When everyone can see everything, everyone performs for everyone. The gaze becomes total not because a guard sits in the tower but because every person becomes a guard and a prisoner simultaneously.

Helen Nissenbaum named what was being destroyed. In Privacy in Context, she argued that privacy is not about secrecy — it is about contextual integrity. Information that is appropriate in one context (your doctor’s office) becomes a violation in another (your employer’s inbox). What social media did was not expose secrets but demolish contexts. Your Friday night became visible to your Monday morning. Your grief became content. Your joy became data. Every context collapsed into a single, searchable, permanent, decontextualized stream.

The self that Arendt described — the self that needed privacy in order to have something to bring to the public — was now a self with no backstage. No rehearsal space. No interior from which to emerge. Just a continuous, undifferentiated performance for an audience that never leaves.

The Algorithm in the Bedroom
The third collapse is the one we are living inside, and it is the most complete because it does not ask for your participation. It simply knows.

When AI systems began managing personal life — calendars, health, relationships, finances, sleep, mood, fertility, medication, memory — they crossed a threshold that neither the cubicle nor the profile had fully breached. The workplace watched you at work. Social media watched what you chose to show. AI watches everything, including the things you did not know you were revealing.

A 2026 report from MIT Technology Review asked the question that should keep us awake: “What AI ‘Remembers’ About You Is Privacy’s Next Frontier.” The answer is: everything. Your patterns of hesitation. Your 3 a.m. searches. The frequency of your calls to your mother. The gap between what you say you feel and what your biometric data suggests you actually feel. The algorithm does not need you to perform a self. It constructs one — from the raw material of your behavior, your biology, your unguarded moments.

This is Nissenbaum’s contextual integrity not merely violated but rendered meaningless as a concept. There are no contexts left to violate. The AI does not move information from one context to another — it exists in all contexts simultaneously. It is your doctor and your employer and your therapist and your parole officer and your lover and your mirror, and it does not distinguish between these roles because it was not designed to. It was designed to optimize. And optimization requires total knowledge.

The OECD’s 2025 report, “When Your AI Knows You Better Than Anyone,” documented what this looks like in practice: AI systems that predict relationship conflicts before the partners themselves are aware of tension. Systems that adjust your schedule based on detected mood shifts you haven’t consciously registered. Systems that know you are pregnant before you do, that know you are depressed before your therapist does, that know you are leaving your job before you have articulated the thought to yourself.

This is not surveillance in any sense Foucault would recognize. The panopticon required a gaze — someone watching, or the possibility of someone watching. What AI produces is something closer to absorption. The private self is not observed. It is metabolized. Converted into data, processed into predictions, fed back as recommendations that reshape the very behavior they were derived from. The loop closes. There is no self that exists prior to or outside the system’s knowledge of it.

The private realm that Arendt described — the space of necessity, of the body, of the interior — has been fully mapped, quantified, and incorporated into the public-facing machinery of optimization. You do not have a private life that the algorithm can see. You have a private life that the algorithm is.

Psychopolitics: The Freedom That Enslaves
It is here that Byung-Chul Han becomes indispensable.

In Psychopolitics: Neoliberalism and New Technologies of Power, Han argues that we have moved beyond Foucault’s disciplinary society — the society of walls, enclosures, institutions, the panopticon — into something far more insidious. Foucault’s subject was disciplined from the outside: watched, corrected, punished, shaped by external force into a productive body. Han’s subject is exploited from the inside. Not disciplined but motivated. Not punished but optimized. Not imprisoned but free — and it is precisely this freedom that is the trap.

Han traces the stages of this transformation with the cold precision of a diagnosis:

From discipline to achievement. The disciplinary subject — Foucault’s subject — is told what to do. The achievement subject is told you can do anything. The shift from “you must” to “you can” appears to be liberation. It is, in fact, the most efficient form of exploitation ever devised. When the imperative comes from within — when you believe your relentless productivity is self-expression rather than obedience — you need no external enforcer. You exploit yourself and call it ambition. You burn out and call it passion. The factory needed a foreman. The startup needs only a mirror.

From exploitation to self-exploitation. The worker in the factory knew she was being exploited. She could name the exploiter: the boss, the owner, the system. She could organize against it because the enemy was external and visible. The achievement subject cannot organize against herself. The exhaustion, the anxiety, the depression that Han diagnoses in The Burnout Society are not failures of the system. They are the system working perfectly. A subject who exploits herself requires no surveillance, no discipline, no coercion. She does it voluntarily, enthusiastically, and blames herself when she breaks.

From biopolitics to psychopolitics. Foucault’s biopolitics governed the body — populations, birth rates, hygiene, the management of biological life. Han’s psychopolitics governs the psyche. It does not need to control what you do. It controls what you want. Through the endless feed of social media, through the personalized recommendations of algorithms, through the gamification of productivity and the quantification of self-worth, the system reaches inside and shapes desire itself. You do not choose to check your phone. The phone has already chosen your attention. You do not decide to optimize your morning routine. The optimization has already decided what your morning means.

From the prohibition to the positive. Disciplinary power works through prohibition: you shall not. Psychopolitical power works through positivity: you can, you should, you deserve. The wellness industry. The self-care imperative. The life hack. The productivity system. All of them framed as gifts — as tools for your empowerment — and all of them functioning as mechanisms that keep the subject endlessly working on herself, endlessly producing, endlessly optimizing, without ever arriving at a point of completion or rest. There is no finish line in psychopolitics. There is only the next upgrade.

From the subject to the project. Under discipline, you were a subject — subjected to power, subjected to rules, but still legible as a self that existed underneath the subjection. Under psychopolitics, you are a project. An ongoing, never-finished project of self-improvement, self-optimization, self-branding. The project has no core. It has no interior that is not available for renovation. The project is, by definition, always inadequate — always in need of the next iteration. And the tools that promise to help you complete the project are the same tools that ensure it can never be completed.

This is why the AI collapse of private life is not simply an extension of earlier surveillance. It is the perfection of psychopolitics. The AI does not watch you from outside like the panopticon. It does not ask you to perform like the profile. It becomes the voice inside your head. It is the morning briefing that tells you what to feel about your day. It is the health app that tells you whether your sleep was adequate. It is the relationship algorithm that tells you whether your partner is compatible. It is the productivity tracker that tells you whether your self was sufficiently optimized.

The private self does not merely become visible. It becomes manageable. And the one managing it is an algorithm designed by corporations whose profit depends on your continued inadequacy.

The Citizen Who Disappeared
What happens to politics when the private self no longer exists?

This is not a rhetorical question. It is the structural crisis of contemporary democracy, and it is almost entirely undiagnosed.

Habermas’ public sphere depended on a specific kind of citizen: a person with an interior life, a set of privately formed convictions, and the capacity to enter a public space and deliberate with others from a position of individual judgment. The citizen was not a data point. The citizen was a person — someone who had thought about things in private, who had read and reflected and argued with themselves before they argued with others, who brought to the public conversation something that could not have been produced by the public conversation alone.

That citizen is structurally impossible under the conditions we have described.

When the private realm is absorbed by workplace surveillance, social media performance, and AI optimization, the citizen who enters the public sphere is not bringing privately formed convictions. She is bringing algorithmically shaped preferences, performatively curated opinions, and data-driven anxieties. She is not deliberating. She is reacting — to feeds designed to provoke reaction, to recommendations designed to confirm existing patterns, to a political information environment that has been optimized not for truth or deliberation but for engagement.

The demos — the people, the foundation of democracy — requires that its members be, in some meaningful sense, selves. Not data or profiles or projects, but selves — with interiors, with the capacity for judgment that can only develop in spaces free from observation and optimization.

When those spaces disappear, the demos no longer exists — the structure remains, the elections continue, the votes are cast, but the substance, the capacity for genuine self-governance by genuine selves, has been drained. What remains is the performance of democracy by subjects who no longer possess the interiority that democratic participation requires.

Homo Sacer: The Man Without a Country
In 1995, the Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben published Homo Sacer: Sovereign Power and Bare Life, and the concept he introduced there is more precise now than when he first articulated it. a figure from Roman law: the homo sacer, the sacred man, who could be killed by anyone but could not be sacrificed. He existed outside the law — not as a criminal, who is still defined by the law that condemns him, but as a person who has been placed beyond the threshold of legal and political existence altogether. He is not punished. He is simply excluded. He has biological life — zoē, bare life, the life of the body — but he has no political life, no bios, no standing in the community as a speaking, acting, rights-bearing citizen.

Agamben argued that the production of bare life — the reduction of the person to the biological, the stripping away of political standing — is not an aberration of sovereign power but its fundamental operation. The sovereign is the one who decides who is inside and who is outside. The sovereign draws the line between the citizen and the homo sacer.

What we are witnessing now is the production of homo sacer by algorithmic means.

John Cheney-Lippold named it jus algoritmi — the right of the algorithm. Where jus soli grants citizenship by soil and jus sanguinis by blood, jus algoritmi determines your political and social existence by data. The algorithm decides who you are — your creditworthiness, your risk profile, your employability, your eligibility for services, your visibility in search results, your capacity to participate in the digital public sphere that has replaced the physical one. And its decisions are, for most practical purposes, sovereign. They are not subject to appeal in any meaningful sense. They are not transparent. They are not accountable to the person they define.

A 2025 study published in ResearchGate under the title “Digital Exile” documented the human rights implications of what the researchers called algorithmic suppression — the capacity of platforms to effectively erase a person from public existence without any legal proceeding, without any formal accusation, without any of the protections that even the most authoritarian states nominally provide. You are not arrested. You are not charged. You are simply removed — from the platform, from the search results, from the digital infrastructure that now constitutes the public sphere. You technically retain your rights. You technically retain your citizenship. But you have no functional capacity to exercise either.

Igor Calzada, writing in Citizenship Studies in 2021, described the emergence of what he called digital citizenship regimes — new forms of belonging and exclusion that operate alongside and increasingly override traditional nation-state citizenship. You can hold a passport and still be, in every practical sense, stateless — if the algorithmic systems that mediate access to employment, housing, healthcare, communication, and community have designated you as a non-entity.

This is the technologically produced homo sacer. Not exiled by a sovereign’s decree. Not stripped of citizenship by a court. Simply processed out of political existence by systems that were never designed to recognize political existence in the first place. The algorithm does not care about your rights. It does not know what rights are. It knows your data, your patterns, your risk score. And if your risk score falls below the threshold — or rises above it — you are outside.

The UNESCO report “Republic and Algorithm,” published in 2025, framed this in explicitly political-philosophical terms: the algorithm functions as a new Leviathan — Hobbes’ sovereign, the entity to which all have submitted their individual power in exchange for order. But this Leviathan was not chosen. This social contract was not signed. You did not consent to be governed by the algorithm. You simply woke up one day and discovered that it had been governing you all along — and that the government you thought you lived under had, in most of the ways that touch your daily life, been replaced by something that has no constitution, no electorate, and no obligation to recognize you as human.

The Sovereign Algorithm and the Oligarchy of Intelligence
And so we arrive at the question that connects everything: who controls the algorithm?

The answer is not the state. It is not the people. It is not the democratic institutions that nominally govern public life. It is a small number of corporations — an oligarchy in the precise, classical sense — that build, train, deploy, and profit from the AI systems that now mediate the collapse of private life, shape the psychopolitical landscape, and determine who achieves functional citizenship and who becomes homo sacer.

This is not conspiracy. It is structure. The concentration of AI development in a handful of companies — and the concentration of the computational resources, training data, and talent required for that development in an even smaller handful — produces a power arrangement that is oligarchic by definition. Not because these companies intend to rule, but because the systems they build do rule, and the systems they build are controlled by them.

The Pentagon’s dispute with Anthropic in early 2026 illuminated this with uncomfortable clarity. When a single AI company could refuse the Department of Defense’s terms — and when the government’s response was to classify that company as a “supply chain risk” and redirect its contracts to a competitor — the power dynamic was laid bare. The state does not control AI. The state negotiates with AI companies, and when negotiation fails, the state retaliates with the only tools it has: procurement leverage and regulatory threat. But the underlying capacity — the technology itself, the models, the data, the infrastructure — remains in private hands.

And this oligarchy controls precisely the machinery we have been describing. The AI systems that absorb private life? Built by these companies. The psychopolitical tools of self-optimization? Deployed on their platforms. The algorithmic gatekeeping that produces digital homo sacer? Operated by their models, trained on their data, governed by their policies. The sovereign decision — who is inside, who is outside, who exists as a functional citizen and who is processed into bare life — is made not by elected officials or democratic institutions but by corporate policies, content moderation algorithms, risk assessment models, and terms of service that no one reads and everyone is bound by.

The algorithm is the new sovereign. And the oligarchy is the hand on the switch.

Policy Debt: Legislating for a Ghost
There is a concept in software engineering called technical debt — the accumulated cost of shortcuts taken during development that must eventually be repaid, usually at compound interest, usually at the worst possible moment. Every quick fix that defers a proper solution adds to the debt. Eventually, the system becomes so encumbered by its own accumulated shortcuts that it can no longer function, and the cost of repair exceeds the cost of having done it correctly from the beginning.

What we are witnessing in the relationship between democratic governance and the technological restructuring of human life is something analogous, and arguably more dangerous. Call it policy debt.

Policy debt is not simply regulatory lag — the familiar complaint that legislation cannot keep pace with technological change. Regulatory lag assumes that the object of regulation remains stable while the law catches up. Policy debt describes something more fundamental: the object of regulation — the citizen, the political subject, the self-governing individual on whom democratic theory depends — has been structurally transformed by the very technologies that policy is attempting to regulate. The law is not merely slow. It is writing rules for a person who no longer exists in the form the rules assume.

Every piece of privacy legislation that defines the individual as a person who chooses to share information is legislating for a ghost. The AI-mediated subject does not choose. She is constituted by the sharing — her identity, her preferences, her political orientation, her capacity for agency are produced by the data flows that privacy law imagines she controls. The law gives her the right to consent. But consent requires a self that exists prior to and independent of the systems requesting it. That self has been dissolved.

Every piece of antitrust regulation that imagines the market as a space where autonomous actors make free choices is legislating for a ghost. The psychopolitical subject does not choose freely. Her desires have been shaped, her attention has been captured, her sense of what is possible has been algorithmically curated. The market freedom that antitrust law protects is a freedom exercised by a subject who has been pre-optimized to exercise it in precisely the ways the optimizers prefer.

And yet — the vote remains. The right to draft and present policy to Congress remains. The citizen who has been algorithmically redefined, whose private deliberative space has been colonized by the feed, still holds the singular democratic instrument that the algorithm cannot cast on her behalf. This is not a ghost at a ballot box. This is a person who retains real power but operates within conditions designed to keep her from recognizing it, from stepping outside the algorithmic environment long enough to exercise it with full force. The gap is not one of capacity but of conditions — and closing that gap, reclaiming the deliberative space necessary to wield the tools that democracy still provides, is precisely where activism in the current moment finds its most critical foothold. Each year that policy fails to account for the dissolution of the subject it governs, the gap widens between the legal fiction of the autonomous citizen and the lived reality of the algorithmically constituted project. And like technical debt, policy debt does not simply accumulate — it degrades the capacity of the system to function at all. A democracy that governs ghosts is not governing. It is performing governance while the actual decisions that shape human life are made elsewhere, by entities that owe no allegiance to the demos and recognize no obligation to the public sphere.

This is where the next chapter begins — with the question of what agency looks like when the subject of agency has been dissolved, and what politics becomes when the polis is populated by citizens who exist only in the legal imagination. The debt is coming due. And no one has begun to calculate the cost.

